column168: These drums were picked up from the generator and inspected prior to loading onto the CH vehicle for transport. After a short trip to the Boynton Beach Clean Harbors facility, the drums were being unloaded. It was during the unloading of the drums that a small released quantity, approximately 2 oz., of material was observed on the truck. The leaking drum was identified and the pinhole leak was identified. An employee wiped across the pinhole leak with an absorbent towel. When he wiped the area of the pinhole leak, the corroded area flaked off creating a larger release, approximately 1.75 gal. that was contained and remediated. The drum was overpacked in a salvage drum along with all of the absorbent material that was used in the remediation efforts.
column169: A Management Team Investigation was conducted regarding this in-transit release. It was noted that the driver did inspected the drums prior to loading them onto his vehicle, however, his efforts were more focused on the closure of the drums rather than the  body of the drums. It was revealed that the drums had what is perceived a heavy layer of dust on the exterior of the drum that may have concealed the area of corrosion that ultimately resulted in the release. Additional training will be completed by the driver that accepted the drums regarding container inspection and external contamination of drums prior to accepting them for transportation.

column168: During a routine yard inspection, FRA Inspector heard a hissing sound and smelled a "solvent" odor around tank car TILX 190656.  Car was isolated and not picked up by train.  NS contractor was called to respond and found the manway bolts less than tool tight.  Contractor was unable to stop leak by tightening bolts.  Bolts were loosened and gasket replaced.   Manway cover was then  re-secured with a wrench in a star pattern and checked for vapor tightness with a flammable gas meter.  No hits on meter after securement.

column168: At 07:08 EST - ERTS was contacted (MC Tank Transport) regarding a rollover accident located at the intersection of Jae Valley Rd/Aerospace Rd. in Roanoke VA. The caller is unsure how much Diesel Fuel and Anti-freeze has spilled, but it has only impacted soil and possibly a nearby ditch. The caller also advised a resin product (UN3257) was in the tanker and an unknown amount leaked onto soil. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor who reported that approximately 1 gallon of UN3257 release from the dome lid to the soil shoulder of the roadway. The contractor was able to tighten the dome lid bolt and the release stopped. The contractor tapped a hole into the tanker and transloaded the remaining product into a replacement CTMV. Approximately 1 gallon of UN3257 was released to the asphalt roadway during transfer operations. The contractor utilized granular absorbents and hand tools to clean the impacted areas. The contractor hand dug the 2ft x 6ft area of impacted soil. All wastes were collected and containerized for pending disposal

column168: On 1-3-2021 at 2300 hrs., I, John Vergis Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE, was contacted by the WLE Dispatcher about a leaking tank car BAPX 222437 that was leaking from the bottom outlet valve in Rook Yard.  The yard crew of Rook Yard found this leak while switching cars in the Runner Track. I called Specialized Professional Services out of Washington, PA to come out and look at the car.  They were on site just after midnight.  They confirmed that the car was leaking from the bottom outlet valve at the valve stem packing.  They said that they were not able to get a tool on the packing bolts to try to tighten the packing to get the leak to stop so they installed a Haz Hammock under the car to catch any drips.  The valve was leaking at about 1 gallon per hour.  It was determined that this car would need to be transloaded.  On 1-4-2021, we were able to located a receiving car PROX 44106.  BAPX 222437  was transferred into PROX 44106 on 1-4-2021 by Enviroserve out of North Canton, Ohio.  On January 6, 2021, Enviroserve came back to the yard to clean the car to get it ready for transportation.  On January 12, 2021, MarkWest obtained a movement approval to send the car to Home Shop.  NARRI:  2(5+5) x (2+0)=40        Cause Codes: 548

column168: Upon arrival at the destination terminal a drum was discovered leaking inside the trailer. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor who utilized a vacuum truck to collect the free liquids from the asphalt parking lot and facility containment area. All recovered liquid product was then transferred into poly IBCs to be filtered and re-used by Howard Sheppard Inc. No other waste was generated.

column168: ODC CLERK CONDUCTING INTERNATIONAL AUDIT, INVOICE STATED "INSECTICIDE" AND THE PACKAGE HAD AN AEROSOL 'RATTLE'. SHE BROUGHT IT TO AN ACCEPTANCE AUDITOR AND THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED FOR INSPECTION, REVEALING: AN INNER BOX WITH A LIMITED QUANTITY MARK   MARKED "LEVEL 3 AEROSOL"   "CONTENTS IN AEROSOL CANS". THIS INNER BOX WAS OPENED TO REVEAL 12 AEROSOL CANS OF INSECTICIDE. THE OUTER PACKAGE HAD NO MARKS OR LABELS INDICATING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. column168: While performing a transfer of HCL from damaged car OLNX 3414 into receiving car TILX 110080, the receiving car was overfilled.  After performing an investigation, it was found that receiving car arrived with a heel of approximately 2400 gallons before starting the transfer.  Due to the close proximity of occupied buildings and adjacent properties, the empty tank cars were not opened to verify it was empty prior to performing the transfer due to the risk of hydrochloric acid vapors being released.  The actual release of HCL was from the vapor scrubber drum connected to the vapor valve.  HCL filled the tank shell then flowed through the vapor valve down the connected hose and overflowed the scrubber drum.  All valves were immediately closed on both cars and the overflow ceased.  Approximately 10 gallons of the HCL spilled onto the hard packed gravel around the drum.  The spill was neutralized and recovered with absorbents.  The gravel area was over-excavated as well.  The excess lading in TILX110080 was returned to OLNX3414 to be transferred to a truck later.

column168: Consignee found tank car TILX362202 dripping from the bottom outlet valve (BOV) cap prior to receiving the tank car in their facility.  Upon inspection by a contractor for NS, the leak was found to be the result of the BOV cap having a bad gasket.  The valve was in the closed position indicating a possible defect in the ball valve.  Thread sealant was applied to the BOV cap and tightened in place which stopped the leak.  A different consignee located nearby agreed to take the car for off loading.  The car was off loaded and the shipper applied for an OTMA to Home Shop the car.

column168: On Monday, January 18, 2021, at approximately 11:30 am, our 0700 job found UTLX 631962 with signs of leaking from the top. They immediately notified management and got to a safe location. Management responded and confirmed that the car was leaking at some point; however, there was currently no active leak at the time found as the ground was dry as well as the side of the car. There was a white, flaky residue present. M&ET management contacted the consignee (Northstar Chemical) for assistance. Their hazmat team came and identified that the gasket was bad and needed to be replaced. Northstar Chemical Hazmat team replaced the bad gasket and installed a new one. M&ET then transported the car to their facility to be unloaded and cleaned. During their inspection of the car, they found that the top hatch/dome wasn't secured properly and they determined that the shipper didn't prepare/secure the car properly for shipment.
column169: M&ET worked with Northstar to contact the shipper of the incident and shared our findings with them. We have requested that they provide us with a corrective action plan after their investigation of the incident is complete.  I have contacted FRA Hazmat inspector Nick Buie to share what transpired and asked for his help with this as well.  While it is not known if the car was in this condition at interchange, M&ET is working with the train crew to ensure they do not miss this at interchange and accept for transportation.

On 12/23/2020 at 0945 ET, one (1) 55 - gallon metal drum of UN1993, Flammable liquid, nos, 3, PGIII "Herbalime" was punctured by a forklift while loading. As a result, approximately 50 gallons of Herbalime released impacting a 100' by 20' area of the trailer floor and asphalt below. Hepaco was dispatched to the site to perform cleanup activities. Granular absorbents were applied to the impacted area of the asphalt to absorb and solidify the released product. The spent absorbents were then collected and containerized. Fans were utilized to vent out the trailer for several days until the trailer could be unloading and decontaminated. The damaged drum was later placed in an overpack drum and the trailer was fogged to reduce the odor present. The waste generated was staged onsite.

column168: On 01/20/2021, at 1212 hours, A FRA inspector in the CSXT Manville Yard Manville NJ discovered SHPX222997 and the SHPX223019, Loaded tank railcars of UN1993 Flammable Liquid (Acetone Toluene) ,having a Vapor  release from the vacuum relief devices. The railcars were isolated and National Response Center and the NJ Department of environment were notified. The emergency response telephone number on the waybill was contacted, (CHEMTREC Report #210120155105), and Veolia the shipper of record was notified. Marion Environmental a CSX response contractor was dispatched to the scene and found the vacuum relief device on both railcars having a vapor release. The Vacuum relief device was removed and replaced with a plug securing the release. The release was secured and corrective actions were communicated to the FRA, and the shipper. The railcar was placed on Hazmat hold and will require Shippers MRU to correct the defects. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required?

column168: During air unloading procedure using less then 15 psi, a minor leak occurred between the Customer's valve and transfer hose due to a bad 3" rubber gasket. Driver shut-down procedure and proceeded to release pressure from trailer before attempting to disconnect transfer line to replace gasket. When driver opened 1/2" ball-valve to fixed stainless steel air supply line located at front of trailer on passenger side, approximately 1 quart of product sprayed out toward driver making contact with both ungloved hands resulting in chemical exposure and spill outside of containment area.     Actions Taken: 1. Spill cleaned-up by on-site personnel.  2. Rubber Gasket and transfer hose replaced resulting in approximately 4 gallons of product being drained and disposed of.  3. Driver utilized on-site eye-wash/safety shower to rinse product from hand and did not need on-site medical treatment. 4. Driver was able to complete transfer without further incident.  5. As a precaution, driver was sent to local clinic in Chattanooga, TN. the next day (1-7-21) for evaluation. Clinic issued driver ointment  to apply to exposed areas, however, driver advised clinic that the spots on his hands were not due to incident and that he was not injured due to this incident.
column169: Root Cause: Due to manufacture's  design and location of operating valves at rear of trailer, the fact that the rear of trailer was lowered into containment area for transfer purposes, and the fact that the transfer process was incomplete; product was forced into fixed air supply line (unknowingly to driver) causing exposure and spill. Secondary cause of exposure was due to the fact that the driver was not wearing protective chemical gloves.   Corrective Actions:  1. Driver retrained on specific operations of trailer.  2. Driver counselled on always wearing required Personal Protective Equipment (PPE).  3. New procedure establish for this specific scenario requiring all drivers to pull trailer to level ground before attempting to release pressure from trailer.

Driver arrived at Shipper to reload trailer with same product (top-load) and discovered trailer had approximately 1,400 gallons of product Heel remaining in tank from previous load. Shipper then decided to load on top of existing product. When driver positioned under loading rack, Olin employee opened dome-lid at rear of trailer and dome-lid burst open barely missing employee resulting in a spill of a quart or less of product and spying employee. Immediately after employee was exposed, employee utilized on-site eye-wash/safety shower and was transported to local hospital for evaluation per protocol.   Upon further investigation, it was discovered that the trailer was still pressurized from previous delivery which was unknown to Olin employee and driver at the time resulting in dome-lid bursting open. It was later reported that the Olin employee was not injured and no treatment was required.
column169: Root Cause: 1. Previous driver failed to follow established policy and procedure related to releasing air pressure and physically checking for remaining product (Heel).  2. Shipper employee failed to follow established Olin policy and procedure related to confirming trailer was not pressurized.   Corrective Action: 1. Previous driver counselled on following policy and procedure via progressive discipline.  2. Carrier and Shipper policy and procedures related to "pre-checklist" reviewed and new procedure was established requiring driver to not only check pressure gauge of trailer to confirm tank is not pressurized, but to also open manifold then open pressure release valve to confirm pressure is released prior to opening dome-lid/loading.

Driver spent the night @ Pilot Travel Center in Elm Creek, N. He woke up at 6 AM pulled to the fuel island. Pulled forward after fueling and Found fluid leaking from his back doors. Freight was Alcohols NOS. UN 1987 The pilot mgmt brought out spill pads and containment snake. They opened the back doors and allowed it to air the driver then went inside to find a small split in the tote bladder. They packed snake and pads around the tote and waited for HazMat Response Inc to arrive for cleanup.                                                                                                          HAZMAT RESPONSE Shifted the load to access the leaking tote. Pulled it to the back and pumped it off into an empty clean 275 Gal and into a separate 50 Gal plastic drum for the additional excess. The Totes loaded were 330gal capacity. Loaded to approx 300 Gal. 50-gallon drum held 15-20 gallon. Lost approximately 15 gallons.
column169: The totes with plastic bladders had been loaded then stored outside in sub freezing tempature. They were snowcovered. The driver was not allowed to watch the load from other than inside the cab of his truck. Therefore as the snow melted into the floor of the trailer and visually there was no notice of a leak. The next day when he saw the leak and then could smell the alcohol is when he found the isue. The shipper should have addressed the freezing conditions and reinspected the totes prior to loading.

Driver was dispatched to the customer location, Alliance Tubular Products at 640 Keystone St., Alliance, OH 44601, for pick-up of a shipment of spent sulfuric acid for disposal. After positioning his truck in the appropriate loading area, a site operator opened the cargo tanker hatch and began top-loading the spent acid. Driver exited the vehicle and quickly realized he failed to close the rear bottom valve before departure to the site. Driver closed the valve immediately and site employees reacted swiftly to the spill. Site employees indicated approximately 8 gallons of the spent material was spilled. Absorbent media was used and the resulting media was containerized for disposal.
column169: As part of our continual improvement program, details of the incident were communicated to all drivers. Aside from the immediate notification, all drivers were given further direction on the importance of pre-trip inspections. Additionally, a training meeting is scheduled for February 20, 2021 to review the incident in more detail and discuss ways to prevent recurrence. Finally, after discussion with the customer, upon arrival in the future, our driver and the site operator will communicate before engaging in any loading activity. Our database was also updated to insure these instructions are printed automatically to the driver's work order when dispatched to the site.

On January 5, 2021, at 1715 hours, Mechanical Inspector at the Conrail Morrisville Yard, Morrisville, Pennsylvania reported that an LYBX 4052, a loaded tank car of UN2055 Styrene was dripping slowly from the bottom of the tank car. The tank car was removed from the outbound train and isolated with containment placed beneath the BOV. The shipper, Lyondell Chemicals, was notified by Rhom and Haas-DOW (consignee). Marion Env. a Conrail emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Morrisville Yard as well as representatives from Conrail and Dow. Marion found that the leak was from the tank car flange above bottom outlet valve and the leakage was unable to be stopped. The shipper was notified of the situation found and was informed the load would be transferred into LYBX 4003 the following day. The load was transferred and subsequently delivered to DOW.  LYBX 4052 was drained of any residual product and is awaiting One Time Movement Approval.  NARRI: 5x(5+1+0)x(2+0) = 60 Cause code:535

On 01/25/21 at approx 12:40 pm, Trainmaster Phil Bailey was notified of a leaking Methanol car.  There was no liquid on the ground, it had evaporated before reaching ground.  FRA Inspector Scott Hoose and Chemtrec were notified (Report #2021-01-25-00144).  Koch Methanol (shipper) was contacted and advised that Young's Environmental will be responding.  Donald Long from Young's Environmental inspected the car and found 2 manway bolts that were not tightened.  Koch Methanol authorized the removal of the seals to inspect the manway gasket, valve plugs, ball valve positions and condition of thread tape.  Everything was found to be in good condition.  Technician quarter-turn tightened the 2 loose manway bolts with a non-sparking pipe wrench.

column168: When loading IBC into trailer material handler observed paint leaking from the bottom of it. Further investigation revealed that the bottom discharge valve had opened on it's own when the IBC was being moved. The valve handle was very sensitive and although no direct action was discovered that caused the valve to open we are assuming that the movement of the IBC caused it to open because of its sensitivity. The spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and the valve was closed and secured shut with a wire tie to prevent it from opening again and moved to ultimate consignee without further incident.
column169: shippers should secure bottom discharge valve handle with some type of securement device to prevent the discharge valve handle from opening and contributing to these types of unintentional releases.

During routine facility inspections, a compromised container was identified. In appropriate personal protective equipment, facility personnel mitigated the impact of the released material, ensuring there was no threat or impact to land, water ways or storm drains; the impact of this release was contained to the warehouse concrete floor. A response team was called to repackage the material into an authorized container for shipment to final destination. During the repacking, it was discovered that the container was not prepared for transportation effectively for the material utilizing stabilizing vermiculite in the outer container. The response team prepared the container and the shipment was sent to its final destination without further incident.
column169: The driver who packaged this container was retrained on more effective techniques for labpacking containers into an outer container.

column161: LISA MARTIN ON BEHALF OF HERITAGE TRANSPORT
column168: Description of Events & Package Failure: While unloading a shipment being received on January 23, 2021, at approximately 12:59 pm a Heritage Environmental Services (“Heritage”) employee operating a fork-truck punctured a tote of waste acid pickle solution with the forks of the forklift.  The tote contained UN3264,CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC, INORGANIC, N.O.S.,(HYDROCHLORIC, NICKEL CHLORIDE),8,PGII,RQ,(D006, D007),ERG#154.  Approximately sixty-five gallons of material was released inside secondary containment in the receiving building of the Part B Permitted Treatment, Storage and Disposal Facility located at Heritage Environmental Services, 8525 NE 38th Street, Kansas City, Missouri.  The fork-truck operator and facility employees immediately began spill response and control procedures.  Response time for the containment and cleanup was approximately 2 hours.  Heritage personnel acted appropriately and promptly in accordance with the Contingency Plan to contain the material.   Material Involved in Incident: Approximately sixty-five gallons of waste acid pickle solution was released, identified on line 1 of manifest 001080073WAS, UN3264,CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC, INORGANIC, N.O.S.,(HYDROCHLORIC, NICKEL CHLORIDE),8,PGII,RQ,(D006, D007),ERG#154.  Heritage Transport had possession of this material as it was manifested to Heritage Environmental Services in Indianapolis, Indiana.  Approximately 863 pounds of clay absorbent and rags were recovered and placed into three 55-gallon containers for proper disposal.
column169: Recommendations/Actions Taken to Prevent Recurrence:  Based on the incident review, the forks of the forklift were too high and punctured a hole in the bottom of the tote.  In order to prevent future recurrence, Heritage conducted an incident review and refresher forklift training with the employee on January, 25, 2021.

column168: On January 29, 2021, at approximately 1:55 AM CST, a representative at the above-referenced R +L Carriers(RLC) location observed one(1) 350-gallon tote containing corrosive material was damaged due to a load shift in transit. As a result, approximately one (1) cup of product released to the adjacent cargo. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES), who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental, LLC(FCE) to perform the necessary corrective action. The crew plugged the damaged area and utilized absorbent pads to remediate the surfaces.

A fiberboard box containing 2 metal bottles, each with approximately 4 L or a fragrance ingredient manufactured by Symrise was observed leaking at the FedEx Express destination station in Pacheco, CA. The cap on one of the bottles loosened during transport and its contents leaked inside the outer fibreboard box. Per the Safety Data Sheet associated with commodities, the contents are classified as UN3082 Environmentally Hazardous Substance Liquid NOS packing group III. There were no dangerous goods markings or labeling on the package, and no Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered with the shipment. However, the net quantity in the individual inner containers does not exceed the allowable amount under IATA Special Provision A197. The station was directed by Dangerous Goods Administration to have FedEx Spill Cleanup staff contain the shipment and hold it pending further disposition instruction.

Our Driver arrived at Associated Grocers in Pembroke, NH and was entering the access road to their parking lot when he suddenly noticed the smell of diesel fuel, and observed product leaking from his tank.  He immediately stopped the truck and retrieved his spill kit. He deployed absorbent pads and damns to minimize the spread of product, and called the safety line. He informed the Safety Manager of his observations and actions, and the Safety Manager immediately notified the local Fire Department. Pembroke Fire responded and was able to slow the leak by applying pads directly to the crack. The Safety Manger coordinated with Dispatch to have nearby trucks respond to assist.  We had one truck just minutes away, And equipped with 7 empty 55-gallon drums.  Our drivers emptied product from the leaking compartment into the drums.  Associated Grocers brought their trucks that needed to be fueled to the location where are truck was leaking, and the driver was able to fuel them from the scene.  When all trucks were fueled . Our nearby tanker had arrived, and all remaining fuel in that pocket was transferred for a second tanker that was nearby and responded to assist.    Pembroke Fire applied speedy dry the product that spilled, and we coordinated with ACV Environmental to respond to clean and dispose of the absorbent materials.

DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Immediately placed in a salvage drum for inspection. column168: A fiberboard box was observed leaking during PM sort: operations at the FedEx Express origin ramp in Berkeley, MO. Further inspection showed that the contents of the package included four metal 1 gallon paint cans. Labeling on the sides of the cans indicated two of them contained Component A, the base for product code PT 799, and the other two contained Component B, the catalyst for product code PT 799. Two of the cans were damaged and leaking. According to the website of the manufacturer, Products Techniques Incorporated, PT 799 is a high performance, two component, polyurethane topcoat designed for exterior use on aircraft ahd other equipment. Per the SDS document associated with that product, the product is classified as Class 3 dangerous goods, specifically UN1263, Paint, packing group II. There were no UN Number or Proper Shipping Name markings and no hazard class label on the package. Also, no Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered by the shipper. The ramp was directed by Dangerous Goods Administration to have FedEx Spill Cleanup staff contain the shipment in a salvage drum and hold it pending further disposition instruction.

column168: The material had been loaded onto a storage tanker earlier for the purpose of heating it to the customer specified temperature as the delivery tanker was not insulated and did not have heating coils. The order was for 42,000 lbs which is 5,198 gallons. It was overlooked that the delivery tanker had a maximum capacity of 5,100 gallons. Normally this material, which comes in totes, would be put in a hotbox to heat prior to loading. It is then transferred directly from the totes to the delivery tanker. In this case, there was an emergency order from the customer, and it was determined that the material could be heated to the specified temperature in a much shorter time by loading it on a tanker with heating coils. The tankers were connected to each other, and the transfer of materials was started. At this point, the employee who initiated the transfer went to the control room to eat lunch. The tanker loading area cannot be seen from the control room. When he returned, he found that the delivery tanker had overflowed, and product was on the ground. He then called the production supervisor for instructions. He was instructed to contain the spill to prevent it from entering any drains and absorb as much of it as possible using Green Stuff. None of the material entered a drain but some did run off the edge of the concrete onto a graveled area contaminating the dirt to a depth of 2-3 inches. As we had rain impending later in the day, we rented a small excavator. Maintenance dug out the contaminated dirt and put it in open top drums for disposal. The Green Stuff was also scraped and shoveled off the concrete into open top drums for disposal.

column168: On 01/29/2021, at approximately 1200, Dangerous Goods Administration received a message from Employee#91918 at the San Juan Ramp, reporting a spill incident with an undeclared dangerous goods shipment. The incident was discovered by the agent during offloading. Per the agent, A pallet with 4 AGM sealed lead acid batteries was loaded into a ULD. The pallet was wrapped with multiple layers of shrink wrap to the degree that the batteries were not ascertainable. The agent discovered that one if the batteries had fallen off of the pallet, resulting in the battery's terminal covers shattering and terminals coming in contact in the aluminum floor of the ULD container. This caused the battery to creak. The agent discovered evidence of charring on the container's aluminum floor and on the battery. Due to the evidence of a dangerous evolution if heat, an NRC report was filed under NRC# 1296994. The battery shipment was Not marked, labeled, nor packaged per IATA Regulations, neither was dangerous goods paperwork included. The shipment is being held for an FAA investigation.

column168: On January 29, 2021, at approximately 12:25 AM CST, a representative with R+L Carriers(RLC) observed two(2) 55-gallon drums of UN1210 that had been damaged with a fork lift while unloading. As a result, approximately forty(40) gallons of UN1210 was released to the trailer floor and concrete surface below. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES), who dispatched personnel from Marion Environmental, Inc.(MEI) to perform the necessary corrective action. Crews collected and containerized the damaged drums into two(2) 85-gallon overpack drums and left on-site for transport and disposal by MEI personnel at a later date. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the impacted areas and worked them in with hand tools. Residual product was removed from the trailer floor with a degreasing agent and bleach. Crews performed several lift tests on the impacted surface and was able to get the UN1210 to reconstitute. After speaking with RL representative, Mr. Noah Gannon, the trailer will be taken out of service and pressure washed by RL personnel at a later date. All UN1210 impacted material was collected and containerized into three(3) 55-gallon drums and left on site for transport and disposal at a later date by MEI personnel. Crews secured the site and scheduled their return at a later date to collect the drums of waste.

column168: The material had been loaded onto a storage tanker earlier for the purpose of heating it to the customer specified temperature as the delivery tanker was not insulated and did not have heating coils. The order was for 42,000 lbs which is 5,198 gallons. It was overlooked that the delivery tanker had a maximum capacity of 5,100 gallons. Normally this material, which comes in totes, would be put in a hotbox to heat prior to loading. It is then transferred directly from the totes to the delivery tanker. In this case, there was an emergency order from the customer, and it was determined that the material could be heated to the specified temperature in a much shorter time by loading it on a tanker with heating coils. The tankers were connected to each other, and the transfer of materials was started. At this point, the employee who initiated the transfer went to the control room to eat lunch. The tanker loading area cannot be seen from the control room. When he returned, he found that the delivery tanker had overflowed, and product was on the ground. He then called the production supervisor for instructions. He was instructed to contain the spill to prevent it from entering any drains and absorb as much of it as possible using Green Stuff. None of the material entered a drain but some did run off the edge of the concrete onto a graveled area contaminating the dirt to a depth of 2-3 inches. As we had rain impending later in the day, we rented a small excavator. Maintenance dug out the contaminated dirt and put it in open top drums for disposal. The Green Stuff was also scraped and shoveled off the concrete into open top drums for disposal.
column169: Remediation/Clean up cost will be submitted on a supplemental report.

column168: 19 Jan 2021 at approx 1700 hrs, container was reported to be Ieaking on the Matson marine terminal in Anchorage; The staff verified that"something" was indeed Ieaking from the container. Absorbent materials were used to contain the small drip and to stabilize the incident. A containment pond was deployed under the container with pads were also used. The hazardous documents were reviewed. The container stopped Ieaking and a clean up company was notified and dispatched for the following morning at 0800 hrs. 20 Jan 2021 at 0800 hrs, US Ecology arrived to conducted an assessment of the incident, to determine the cause of the leak, re-handle the shipment to make it safe and to the clean up inside the container. The bottom layer of a shrink wrapped palletized shipment containing 48(5 gal) drums of Kerosene had 4 compromised drums caused by the cargo shifting;(pic 1) This pallet was not blocked and brace which resulted in shifting during transit. The vessel did report experiencing rough seas and there was no leak noted on the vessel. US Ecology was directed to properly dispose of ALL drums that had ANY defects such as spillage on top, scratches, imperfect label and or dents in the drum. There were 28 drums found with defects.
column169: Shrink wrapping pallets facilitate ease in handling but does not provide sufficient securing of a load neither does it provide an blocking and bracing. The shipper was advised to properly block and brace shipment for the conditions anticipated for ocean transport.

column168: The spill was caused by human error; the driver failed to close an air valve before leaving the plant. The driver left the plant, turned right and began driving up the hill on North Texas Road before he noticed the trailer was leaking product. Upon examination, he quickly learned that he had filed to close the air valve to the top of the trailer. It was estimated that approximately 30 gallons of sulfuric acid was spilled ; 15 gallons on Chemtrade's property and 15 gallons on the roadway. the driver drove about 350 yards total. There was trail of weak sulfuric acid on the ground. The ground was treated with sodium bicarbonate neutralize the ph level. Then, the product was broomed up into a drum. The drum will be profiled and disposed of.
column169: The driver has been retrained to double check all connections and make sure his vehicle is road worthy. This was human error.

column168: Driver was traveling on Route 34 into Shermansdale. The road is on a slight grade and crosses a concrete bridge. Upon discovering the black ice conditions, the driver reduced his speed; estimated at no more than 25 mph. Driver maintained control until the vehicle encountered the bridge that was covered in black ice. The rear wheels of the truck broke traction and the truck began a slow spin until it struck the right guide rail causing it to overturn. The vehicle continued to slide, on its passenger side, across the highway, striking the curb on the opposite side of the road causing the truck to flip to the other side. The force of the flip separated the trucks delivery hose and reel from the truck. This caused a short lived uncontrolled release of product. Emergency controls activated to close the open piping except for minor leak than was closed by the fire dept. and an arriving Heller's employee.
column169: Black ice conditions were being reported by both television and radio stations. Drivers heading out were advised to be cautious of the conditions and stay alert. Rural areas such as Carroll Township in Perry County are manned by a small number of employees who man the cider and plow trucks and are unable to meet the demands when icy conditions present themselves. Fuel delivery companies have little choice when working to meet the needs of customers regardless of weather and road conditions and sometimes roll the dice and hope for the best. As Safety Director, I believe that the driver involved was doing everything possible to maintain control during the difficult conditions that were encountered. He was extremely fortunate that he wasn't injured more severely.

The plow truck was not able to stop or avoid collision and struck the tank truck in the rear of the truck on driver's side. The collision damaged the loading/unloading lines and pumping system of the tank truck and the liquid meter cabinet in the rear of the truck. No hazardous material was released from the tanks.

The driver was attempting to move the hose from one compartment on the trailer to another compartment. The driver failed to tum the pump off prior to disconnecting the hose. As a result, approximately 2 gallons of petroleum products was released. A portion of the petroleum products was able to spray on the driver and he sustained a chemical burn injury to his foot. The driver was able to clean-up the spill without further incident.
column169: KAG West, LLC will continue to train and enforce safe loading/unloading policies and procedures.
